# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1864-national-union-national-convention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The **1831 National Republican National Convention** was held to determine the presidential ticket of the National Republican Party in the 1832 United States presidential election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The convention was held in Baltimore, Maryland in December 1831.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The party nominated Senator Henry Clay of Kentucky for president and former Representative John Sergeant of Pennsylvania for vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The 1831 National Republican National Convention was the first U.S. presidential nominating convention held by a major party, though a third party, the Anti-Masonic Party, had held a presidential nominating convention earlier in 1831.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] 155 delegates from 18 of the 24 states attended the convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Clay was the unanimous choice for president of the party's delegates.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] He was the first sitting member of the United States Senate to be nominated for president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] In the 1832 presidential election, Clay was defeated by President Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] After the 1832 election, the National Republican Party, the Anti-Masonic Party, and other opponents of Jackson coalesced into the Whig Party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Thus, the 1831 convention was the only national convention ever held by the National Republican Party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The **1832 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 21 to May 23, 1832, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the first presidential nominating convention ever held by the Democratic Party, incumbent President Andrew Jackson was nominated for a second term, while former Secretary of State Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Anti-Masonic Party and the National Republican Party had held the first presidential nominating conventions in 1831, and Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet" helped organize a Democratic convention in 1832.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] As the party leaders assumed that Jackson would be nominated for president, the primary purpose of the convention was to find a new running mate: Vice President John C.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun had fallen out with Jackson following the Petticoat affair and the Nullification Crisis, and subsequently resigned the office in order to take a Senate seat.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which was presided over by Governor Robert Lucas, hosted delegates from every state except Missouri; Jackson won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] With Jackson's strong endorsement, Van Buren easily won the vice presidential nomination on the first ballot, defeating former Representative Philip P.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barbour of Virginia and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Jackson and Van Buren went on to win the 1832 presidential election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the summer of 1822, "Richmond Junto" leader Thomas Ritchie of Virginia began raising the idea of a national convention to resolve the issue of nomination; ultimately, the congressional nominating caucus was appealed to by the devotees of Treasury Secretary William H.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Following that defeat in the election of 1824, early in 1827, Van Buren privately made the argument to Richie for an exclusive national convention of Republicans to ensure Jackson's nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] However, it did not immediately come to fruition while state conventions and legislatures took up Jackson as their presidential candidate for the election of 1828 with Vice President John C.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Such a type of national convention would occur after the election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun soon became politically estranged from President Jackson, due in part to an 1830 letter written by Crawford stating that Calhoun, as Secretary of War under President James Monroe, pushed for a reprimand of then-General Jackson for his actions in the 1818 invasion of Florida.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Petticoat affair in which Calhoun's wife, Floride, was a central figure further alienated Jackson from the vice president and his supporters.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The final blow to the relationship came in January 1832, when Calhoun, as President of the Senate, sank Van Buren's nomination as Minister to Great Britain by casting a tie-breaking vote in the United States Senate.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Calhoun was replaced as the party's 1832 vice presidential nominee by Van Buren.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Later that year, on December 28, he resigned as vice president, after having been elected to the U.S.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] There he continued to be a proponent of the doctrine of nullification in opposition to Jackson.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The proposal for the convention began with members of Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet", his coterie of informal advisers and confidants.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Major William Berkeley Lewis wrote on May 25, 1831, to Amos Kendall, who was then in New Hampshire.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] He proposed that the New Hampshire legislature call for a national gathering of Republican supporters of the Jackson administration to nominate a candidate for the vice presidency, and asked Kendall to pass the idea to Isaac Hill.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention was called to order by Frederick A.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from all states except Missouri were present.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Governor Robert Lucas of Ohio served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Peter Vivian Daniel, James Fenner, John M.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barclay, and Augustin Smith Clayton were chosen as convention vice presidents.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] John Adams Dix was appointed secretary at the first meeting, with other additional secretaries thereafter.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] A resolution was passed by the convention requiring two-thirds majority support of the delegates for a nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] An address by the Republican delegates of New York gave a history of previous national political activity in the United States.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] They denounced the National Republicans as Federalists under a new designation and they denounced the Nullifiers while they declared that their own party held the middle ground between the positions of the other two.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The address described what they claimed were political similarities between Andrew Jackson and Thomas Jefferson and it defended the policies of Jackson's administration.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] It characterized Van Buren as a strict constructionist and welcomed his nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention concluded by adopting a resolution calling for an address or report from the delegations to their constituents.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Jackson was nominated via a resolution passed by the convention, affirming the nominations which Jackson had previously received from multiple state legislatures.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president on the first ballot after receiving 208 votes of the 283 cast, 19 more than the two-thirds majority required to win.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren defeated their main competitors, Henry Clay and John Sergeant of the National Republican Party, by a large electoral vote margin in the election of 1832.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The **1835 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 20 to May 22, 1835, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated incumbent Vice President Martin Van Buren for president and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky for vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Former Speaker of the House Andrew Stevenson served as the convention chairman.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] With the support of President Andrew Jackson, Van Buren won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson narrowly won the two-thirds majority necessary for the vice presidential nomination, overcoming a challenge from William Cabell Rives of Virginia.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Van Buren and Johnson went on to win the 1836 presidential election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] On February 23, 1835, President Andrew Jackson wrote to James Gwin of Tennessee and claimed a preference for someone who would "most likely to be the choice of the great body of republicans" in regard to his successor.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] He expressed the desire to hold another national convention to nominate candidates for the presidency and vice presidency.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] He instructed Gwin to show the letter to the editor of the *Nashville Republican*.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The newspaper later reprinted the letter.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Stevenson of Virginia served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Six convention vice presidents and four secretaries were appointed.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Tennessee, Illinois, South Carolina, and Alabama sent no delegates to the convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] President Jackson had long planned for Vice President Martin Van Buren to succeed him, and Van Buren was the unanimous choice of the delegates for the presidency.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Jackson and other major Democrats had settled on Richard Mentor Johnson, a Kentucky representative who had fought in the War of 1812, as Van Buren's running mate, but many Virginia Democrats backed William Cabell Rives, the former Ambassador to France.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] A man from Tennessee, Edward Rucker, who was present at the convention but was not sent as a delegate, cast all 15 votes Tennessee was entitled to for Van Buren, and for Johnson for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was nominated for vice president after winning one vote more than the two-thirds majority required.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The delegation of Virginia declared that it had no confidence in Johnson's character and principles, and would not support him.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Letters went out on May 23 from the convention president and vice presidents asking for the acceptance of the nominations by the nominees.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren replied and accepted the nomination on May 29; Johnson, likewise on June 9.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Whigs did not put forward a national ticket nominated by national convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren defeated his many competitors for the presidency in the general election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] While the electors of Virginia supported Van Buren for the presidency, they cast their vice presidential votes for William Smith.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Johnson received a plurality, but not a majority, of the electoral votes for the vice presidency.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] In the subsequent contingent election in the Senate, Johnson was elected vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The **1839 Whig National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention held from December 4 to December 8 in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] It was the first national convention ever held by the Whig Party, and was organized to select the party's nominee in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The convention nominated former Senator William Henry Harrison of Ohio for president and former Senator John Tyler of Virginia for vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] With Southern delegates united behind him, Clay led on the first presidential ballot, but failed to win a majority.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison won the nomination on the fifth ballot after several delegates switched from supporting Clay or Scott.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The convention chose Tyler, a Southerner and Clay supporter, to serve as Harrison's running mate.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The Whig ticket went on to win the 1840 election, defeating incumbent Democratic President Martin Van Buren.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Clay led on the first ballot, but circumstances conspired to deny him the nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] First, the convention came on the heels of a string of Whig electoral losses, and party members were anxious to reverse the trend.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison managed to distance himself from the losses, but Clay, as the party's philosophical leader, could not.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Had the convention been held in the spring of 1840, when the continuing economic downturn caused by the Panic of 1837 led to a string of Whig victories, Clay would have had much greater support.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Second, the convention rules had been drawn up so that whoever won the majority of delegates from a given state would win all the votes from that state.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Third, several Southern states whose Whig party organizations supported Clay abstained from sending delegates to the convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison won on the fifth ballot after Clay delegates from Illinois and Scott delegates from Michigan, New York, and Vermont combined to switch their support to Harrison.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Writer and activist John Neal, who chaired the delegation from Maine, claimed to have been instrumental in convincing the powerful New York delegation to back Harrison prior to the final vote.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Because Harrison (born in Virginia) was considered a Northerner (as a resident of Ohio), the Whigs needed to balance the ticket with a Southerner.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] They also sought a Clay supporter to help unite the party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] After being turned down by several potential candidates, including John J.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Crittenden, John Bell, and Willie Person Mangum, the convention finally found its Southerner who had faithfully supported Clay and would accept: former Senator John Tyler.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Tyler was well known to the delegates, having previously been the running mate of Hugh Lawson White and Willie Person Mangum during the four-way Whig campaign of 1836.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] He was easily nominated on the first ballot.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] During the balloting, Clay and Scott played cards with two Whig politicians, John J.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Crittenden and George Evans, at the Astor House hotel in New York City.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] When the group received word of Harrison's victory, Clay blamed his loss on Scott and punched him, hitting the shoulder which had been wounded during Scott's participation in the Battle of Lundy's Lane, before being physically removed from the hotel room.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Scott then sent Crittenden to Clay with Scott's challenge for a duel, but Crittenden reconciled them by convincing Clay to apologize.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Abolitionists held a presidential nominating convention on April 1 and 2, 1840, at the City Hall in Albany, New York, and nominated James G.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney of New York for president and Thomas Earle of Pennsylvania for vice president in the 1840 United States presidential election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Although the name was not in general use at the time, this is considered the founding convention of the Liberty Party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Delegates from six states attended the convention, which was preceded by local abolitionist meetings in the burned-over district of Upstate New York.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] New Yorkers accounted for all but a handful of those present, while the remainder came chiefly from New England.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Winter weather and lack of funds precluded the attendance of delegates from Pennsylvania and the Old Northwest.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Garrisonian abolitionists opposed any involvement in electoral politics and attended with the aim to prevent an independent nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Robust debate between the Garrisonians and the political abolitionists preceded the voting on the second day of the convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The motion to nominate candidates for president and vice president narrowly passed, and the convention named Birney and Earle as the national ticket.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention did not specify a name for the new party, and Birney and Earle were known variously as the Abolitionist, Freemen's, Human Rights, Liberty, and People's ticket.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The pair polled 0.3 percent of the vote in the fall election, which was won by the Whig candidate, William Henry Harrison.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Abolitionists debated their stance on electoralism during the 1830s, with a minority favoring creation of a new abolitionist party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Alvan Stewart and Myron Holley emerged as the most prominent political abolitionists.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The need for political action was evident from the failure of existing institutions to respond to moral suasion.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Initially, most abolitionists preferred to work within the established two-party system.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] By 1839, efforts to influence the Democratic and Whig parties had apparently failed.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Adherents to the philosophy of nonresistance opposed participation in the electoral system as a moral and religious principle.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Many abolitionists believed that political parties were essentially corrupt and warned that a descent into partisanship would undermine the movement's moral message.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Interest in an independent abolitionist party increased following the 1839 Whig National Convention in response to the nominations of William Henry Harrison and John Tyler, both slaveholders, as the national Whig candidates.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley travelled across Upstate New York tirelessly advocating for independent nominations in the fall of 1839.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The New York State Anti-Slavery Society held a convention at the Presbyterian church in Warsaw, New York, on November 13 and 14, 1839.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The more than 500 attendees included abolitionists from Western New York and neighboring Pennsylvania.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Josiah Andrews of Perry, New York, presided over the meeting, while Holley and William L.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Chaplin served on the five-member committee on resolutions.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The sixth resolution endorsing the creation of a new abolitionist party was adopted unanimously.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention nominated Birney for president and Francis Julius LeMoyne of Pennsylvania for vice president, and appointed Holley, Andrews, and Joshua H.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Darling to prepare an address to the electorate.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Both Birney and LeMoyne declined the nomination of the Warsaw convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne felt an independent ticket was untimely and inexpedient, and warned that the action of the convention suggested a worrying lack of confidence in the moral influence of abolitionism.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney approved the principle of independent nominations, but felt the Warsaw convention was not an appropriate venue, and that a candidate should be selected by a national gathering of abolitionists.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] His conditional refusal set in motion the chain of events that would culminate in the first national convention of the unnamed new abolitionist party the following year.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A gathering of between 600 and 700 abolitionists from the vicinity of Genesee County, New York, met at Arcade, New York, on January 28 and 29, 1840.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley and Gerrit Smith were the principal organizers of this meeting.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Reuben Sleeper was president of the convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates met in a temporary structure constructed for the purpose, the village meeting house having been found too small to admit the crowds that flocked from as far away as 60 miles in all directions.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley, Smith, and Chaplin led the political abolitionists on the floor of the convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A large number of antislavery Whigs attended in order to oppose the formation of a new abolitionist party, but were outvoted three to one by the advocates of independent nominations.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The resolutions adopted by the convention denounced the Harrison-Tyler ticket and the Democratic incumbent president Martin Van Buren and endorsed the creation of a new abolitionist party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates called for a national convention of the "friends of the immediate abolition of slavery" to meet at Albany on April 1 to nominate candidates for president and vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The action of the Arcade convention elicited a flurry of controversy.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] William Lloyd Garrison denounced the gathering in the pages of *The Liberator* and mocked the attendees as a handful of fringe "malcontents" claiming to speak for the national abolitionist movement.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Phelps defended political abolitionists against charges of inconsistency and moral laxity, responding that the intransigence of the existing parties created a religious obligation for abolitionists to act independently.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Phelps argued that it was the moral character of politicians, not politics, that led to corruption, and that a new party would invite the participation of Christians alienated by the opportunism of the Whigs and Democrats.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Goodell expressed strong reservations against permanent political parties, and called instead for a temporary, single-issue "union" to contest the 1840 election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] James Gillespie Birney was born in 1792 to a slaveholding Kentucky family.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A graduate of Princeton University, he was admitted to the bar and served as a member of both the Kentucky and Alabama legislatures during the 1810s.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He was an early supporter of the American Colonization Society, which advocated for gradual emancipation and the resettlement of free people of color outside the United States.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In 1836, he became a convert to immediatism, manumitted the enslaved people on his Alabama plantation, and relocated to Cincinnati, where he served as the editor of the *Philanthropist* and an officer in the American Anti-Slavery Society (AASS).
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney opposed independent political action by abolitionists as late as 1838, but by 1839 had become one of the most prominent advocates for a new party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He became aligned with the Anti-Garrisonian faction in the AASS and notably broke with Garrison over the equal participation of women in the society's activities, which Garrison supported and Birney opposed.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Following his conditional reply to the Warsaw convention, which stressed the timing and venue of the nominations, he appeared likely to receive the nomination of the Albany convention when it met in April 1840.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney's candidacy was met with reluctance from some political abolitionists, including Leavitt, Wright, and Smith, who preferred a better-known candidate to head the new party's ticket in the fall campaign.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] When it appeared that no other prominent abolitionist would agree to run, some, including Whittier and Henry B.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Stanton, advised postponing the efforts to organize a new party until after the next election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Francis Julius LeMoyne was born in Pennsylvania in 1798.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He graduated from Washington College in 1815 and later attended Jefferson Medical College.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A wealthy physician notable for his diverse intellectual pursuits, LeMoyne was active in the abolitionist movement in his native state, serving as an agent of the Underground Railroad and as president of the Pennsylvania Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Following the schism of the AASS in May 1840, he served as vice president of the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne opposed the creation of a new party ahead of the 1840 United States elections, which he believed was both premature and dangerously divisive.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He declined the vice presidential nomination of the Warsaw convention when it was offered in November 1839.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In his public reply to the convention, LeMoyne expressed concern that independent nominations would undermine abolitionists' religious message and implied their inability to abolish slavery through moral influence.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Equally seriously, a poor showing in the presidential election would embarrass the abolitionist candidates and expose the movement's internal disunity to public ridicule.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne wrote to Birney that an independent candidacy could permanently alienate Whig and Democratic partisans from the abolitionist movement by forcing them to choose between their antislavery and partisan loyalties.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne's refusal created a vacancy on the ticket that was filled by Thomas Earle, a Hicksite Quaker formerly prominent in the Pennsylvania Abolition Society.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Born in Leicester, Massachusetts, in 1789, Earle attended Leicester Academy.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He relocated to Philadelphia in 1817, where he practiced law.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Earle was previously a member of the Pennsylvania Democratic Party, from which he was expelled for his abolitionist views.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] His state residence and past partisan connections were the chief reasons for his selection by the Albany convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention met at the Albany City Hall on April 1, 1840.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Of the 121 delegates, 104 came from New York alone; Massachusetts sent the next-largest delegation, with 11 delegates.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Winter weather and insufficient funds prevented the attendance of delegates from outside the Northeastern United States.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Several prominent abolitionists who were unable to be present sent letters to be read to the convention, including Whittier, who advised against independent nominations.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Included among the attendees were several who came with the express purpose of opposing a new abolitionist party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Of the new party advocates, Smith was bedridden and unable to travel to Albany, while Birney, as the prospective candidate, was tactfully absent.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Most of the discussion during the two days of the convention focused on whether to support an independent ticket in the 1840 presidential election, with passionate arguments on both sides.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Beman gave a powerful speech ridiculing the new party movement.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] So persuasive were Beman's arguments that Wright predicted, if the delegates had been polled immediately following his remarks, a majority would have voted against the measure.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley, Leavitt, Stewart, Beriah Green, and Benjamin Shaw (who traveled 90 miles on foot from his Vermont residence to attend the convention) spoke in favor of independent nominations.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley spoke immediately after Beman and responded to him directly, arguing for the necessity of a new party; only by independent political action could abolitionists increase their moral influence and demonstrate their consistent opposition to slavery.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Stewart replied that the abolitionists' previous tactics had been ineffective, and only by organizing a new party could they break the hegemony of the Slave Power.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A vote taken on the evening of the second day resulted in a narrow majority for independent nominations, with 44 votes in favor and 33 against, while more than a third of the delegates abstained.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates then proceeded to nominate Birney and Earle for president and vice president by acclamation.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention deliberately avoided the controversial question of whether to form a permanent organization in order to preserve unity between advocates of a new party and those favoring nonpartisan nominations.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Similarly, eager to recruit as widely as possible, the convention avoided addressing other divisive topics in favor of a narrow emphasis on the abolition of slavery.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The platform was deliberately silent on issues apart from slavery; in the event that Birney and Earle were elected, all other questions would be settled according to the greatest good to all citizens.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] It condemned as "treasonable" the congressional gag rule restricting the introduction of antislavery petitions and endorsed renewed moral and religious efforts to abolish slavery in tandem with political action.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates did not specify a name for the new party, if a party it was.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney and Earle were most frequently called the Abolitionist or Independent Abolitionist ticket, although a variety of other names were used, including the Human Rights Party, the People's Party, the Freemen's Party, and the Liberty Party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The last was the invention of Gerrit Smith, who used the name as early as February 1840, and was later formally adopted by the 1841 Liberty National Convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention appointed a national committee consisting of Stewart, Smith, and Goodell to coordinate the campaign.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In response to criticism that a gathering dominated by New Yorkers was hardly a "national" convention, the delegates instructed the committee to hold a ratification meeting at New York City in one month's time.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Delegates from 10 of the 13 free states attended the ratification convention at New York City in May 1840, while many abolitionists were in town for the annual meeting of the American Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The meeting was a landmark event in the history of the AASS, which split definitively when opponents of Garrison left to form the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society, leaving the Garrisonians in control of the Old Organization.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Across town, the ratification convention confirmed the choice of Birney and Earle as the national ticket, as Birney prepared to set sail for London as part of the American delegation to the World Anti-Slavery Convention.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention received mixed responses from abolitionists.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Garrisonians ridiculed the "April Fools' Convention" as ill-considered and unrepresentative of the national abolitionist movement.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Leavitt, in contrast, gave Birney and Earle his unqualified endorsement and became the independent ticket's most enthusiastic supporter.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Some early skeptics, including Whittier, eventually supported Birney after he formally accepted the nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Bailey finally endorsed Birney before the election, although many of his associates in Ohio supported the Whigs.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Most outsiders took little notice of the nominations or dismissed the ticket as a Democratic ploy to divert abolitionist votes from the national Whig candidates.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney remained out of the country until after Election Day and played little part in the campaign.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Few expected the ticket to draw a significant number of votes, least of all Birney himself, who saw his candidacy as a starting point for future efforts.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Electors pledged to Birney and Earle appeared in every free state, where they polled a combined 6,946 votes.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The ticket put up its strongest performances in Massachusetts and New York, which together accounted for more than half Birney's national total.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In Connecticut, Indiana, and New Jersey, political abolitionists remained largely unorganized, and Birney polled only a negligible number of votes in these states.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Altogether, Birney and Earle received 0.3 percent of the national popular vote and no electoral votes, finishing a distant third behind Harrison and Van Buren.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Most abolitionists abstained or voted for the larger parties, while only in Massachusetts did Birney poll more than 1 percent of the votes cast.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The **1840 Democratic National Convention** was held in Baltimore, Maryland, from May 5 to May 6.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic Party re-nominated President Martin Van Buren by acclamation, but failed to select a nominee for vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren is the only major party presidential nominee since the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Dragged down by the unpopularity of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was defeated by the Whig Party's ticket in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from 21 of 26 states were in attendance.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] States not in attendance were Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, South Carolina and Virginia.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The 1840 convention was the first at which the party adopted a platform.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates reaffirmed their belief that the Constitution was the primary guide for each state's political affairs.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] To them, this meant that all roles of the federal government not specifically defined fell to each respective state government, including such responsibilities as debt created by local projects.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Decentralized power and states' rights pervaded each and every resolution adopted at the convention, including those on slavery, taxes, and the possibility of a central bank.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was not retained on the ticket, as he was largely seen as a liability in the 1836 election and had focused much of his time as vice president on his own economic affairs.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Former president Andrew Jackson backed James K.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk for the position of vice president, but Van Buren supported his vice president's renomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Prior to the convention, several prominent Democrats sought the vice presidential nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Among them were Polk; Senator William R.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] King of Alabama; and Secretary of State John Forsyth of Georgia.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The convention ultimately failed to nominate a running mate for Van Buren.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren remains the only major party presidential nominee since the passage of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk and Johnson would both receive electoral votes for vice president in the general election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 30 to December 2, 1840.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the shadow of an incomplete economic recovery from the Panic of 1837, Whig nominee William Henry Harrison defeated incumbent President Martin Van Buren of the Democratic Party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the first of two Whig victories in presidential elections, but was the only one where they won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the third rematch in American history.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In 1839, the Whigs held a national convention for the first time.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1839 Whig National Convention saw 1836 nominee William Henry Harrison defeat former Secretary of State Henry Clay and General Winfield Scott.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren faced little opposition at the 1840 Democratic National Convention, but controversial Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson was not renominated.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats thus became the only major party since 1800 to fail to select a vice presidential nominee.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Referencing vice presidential nominee John Tyler and Harrison's participation in the Battle of Tippecanoe, the Whigs campaigned on the slogan of "Tippecanoe and Tyler Too." With Van Buren weakened by economic woes, Harrison won a popular majority and 234 of 294 electoral votes.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Voter participation surged as white male suffrage became nearly universal, and a contemporary record of 42.4% of the voting age population voted for Harrison.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren's loss made him the third president to lose re-election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs did not enjoy the benefits of victory.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 67-year-old Harrison, the oldest U.S. president elected until Ronald Reagan won the 1980 election, died a little more than a month after inauguration.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was succeeded by John Tyler, who unexpectedly proved not to be a Whig.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] While Tyler had been a staunch supporter of Clay at the convention, he was a former Democrat, a passionate supporter of states' rights, and effectively an independent.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] As President, Tyler blocked the Whigs' legislative agenda and was expelled from the Whig Party, subsequently the second independent (after Washington) to serve as president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren would be the last incumbent president to lose his reelection bid in a general election until fellow Democrat Grover Cleveland in 1888.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time a challenger to an incumbent president got a majority of the vote until 1932.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time as of 2024 where the incumbent president seeking re-election flipped a state yet failed to secure re-election, with Van Buren winning South Carolina, despite losing it four years earlier, and losing re-election to Harrison.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The first national convention of the Whig Party was called for by members of the party in Congress and it was attended by almost 250 delegates in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, William Henry Harrison, and Winfield Scott ran for the party's presidential nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegations of each state balloted separately before meeting together with the other representatives of the states.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Clay initially led on the first ballot, but Harrison won on the final ballot with 148 votes compared to Clay's 90 votes and Scott's 16 votes after supporters from Scott switched to Harrison.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] John Tyler was selected as a factional and geographical balance to Harrison.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic members of the New Hampshire General Court made a call for the 1840 Democratic National Convention which was held in Baltimore, Maryland in May 1840.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates from twenty-two states attended the convention, but the sizes of the delegations varied with New Jersey having fifty-nine delegates to cast its eight votes while Massachusetts only had one delegate to cast its fourteen votes.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] A committee was formed to make recommendations for the nominations and the committee supported Van Buren for renomination which was approved by acclamation.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, the vice-presidential nomination was left vacant due to opposition to Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson's personal life.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After the negative views of Freemasonry among a large segment of the public began to wane in the mid-1830s, the Anti-Masonic Party disintegrated.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Many leaders began to move to the Whig party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Remaining leaders met in September 1837 in Washington, and agreed to maintain the party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The third Anti-Masonic Party National Convention was held in Philadelphia on November 13–14, 1838.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] By this time, the party had been almost entirely supplanted by the Whigs.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates unanimously voted to nominate William Henry Harrison for president (who the party had supported for president the previous election along with Francis Granger for vice president) and Daniel Webster for vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, when the Whig National Convention nominated Harrison with John Tyler as his running mate, the Anti-Masonic Party did not make an alternate nomination and ceased to function and was fully absorbed into the Whigs by 1840.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney, Myron Holley, Joshua Leavitt, and Gerrit Smith proposed the creation of an anti-slavery party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In July 1839, two resolutions proposed by Holley at the American Anti-Slavery Society's meeting in Cleveland, called for the creation of an abolitionist party.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nevertheless, the supporters nominated Birney and Francis Julius LeMoyne as a presidential ticket at a meeting in Warsaw, New York.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, Birney declined the presidential nomination as he preferred a nomination to be made by a regular body of abolitionists and LeMoyne also declined the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Smith and Holley made a call for an abolitionist nominating convention to be held on April 1, 1840, in Albany, New York.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 121 delegates attended the delegation and selected a presidential ticket of Birney and Thomas Earle. which was accepted.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney was unable to campaign during the election as he was in England until November.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party received opposition from followers of William Lloyd Garrison and abolitionist Whigs.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the wake of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was widely unpopular, and Harrison, following Andrew Jackson's strategy, ran as a war hero and man of the people while presenting Van Buren as a wealthy snob living in luxury at the public expense.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Although Harrison was comfortably wealthy and well educated, his "log cabin" image caught fire, sweeping all sections of the country.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison avoided campaigning on the issues, with his Whig Party attracting a broad coalition with few common ideals.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig strategy overall was to win the election by avoiding discussion of difficult national issues such as slavery or the national bank and concentrate instead on exploiting dissatisfaction over the failed policies of the Van Buren administration with colorful campaigning techniques.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was the first president to campaign actively for office.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] He did so with the slogan "Tippecanoe and Tyler too".
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Tippecanoe referred to Harrison's military victory over a group of Shawnee Native Americans at a river in Indiana called Tippecanoe in 1811.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] For their part, Democrats laughed at Harrison for being too old for the presidency, and referred to him as "Granny", hinting that he was senile.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs took advantage of this quip and declared that Harrison was "the log cabin and hard cider candidate", a man of the common people from the rough-and-tumble West.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] They depicted Harrison's opponent, President Martin Van Buren, as a wealthy snob who was out of touch with the people.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, it was Harrison who came from a family of wealthy planters, while Van Buren's father was a tavernkeeper.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison however moved to the frontier and for years lived in a log cabin, while Van Buren had been a well-paid government official.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, the election was held in the wake of the Panic of 1837, one of the worst economic depressions in the nation's history, and voters blamed Van Buren, seeing him as unsympathetic to struggling citizens.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 31.9% of the voting age population and 80.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time that a majority of southern voters participated in the election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison won the support of western settlers and eastern bankers alike.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,179 counties/independent cities making returns, Harrison won in 699 (59.29%) while Van Buren carried 477 (40.46%).
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Three counties (0.25%) in the South split evenly between Harrison and Van Buren.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The extent of Van Buren's unpopularity was evident in Harrison's victories in New York, the president's home state, and in Tennessee, where Andrew Jackson himself had come out of retirement to stump for his former vice-president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time a Democratic president lost re-election, as well as the first of only two times (the other being 1980) that a Democratic president lost re-election and lost the popular vote.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the first election in U.S. history in which a candidate won more than a million popular votes.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election where Indiana voted for the Whigs.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election where the Whigs won Maine, Michigan, and Mississippi.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in American history in which a majority of voters in Alabama and a majority of voters in Mississippi voted for different candidates.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1840 presidential election was the only time in which four people who either had been or would become a U.S.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] President (Van Buren, Harrison, Tyler, and Polk) received at least one vote in the Electoral College when it voted for president and vice-president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison's victory won him precious little time as chief executive of the United States.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After giving the longest inauguration speech in U.S. history (lasting about 1 hour and 45 minutes, in cold weather and rain), Harrison served only one month as president before dying of pneumonia on April 4, 1841.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Source: Data from Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–257.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the 1997 film *Amistad*, Van Buren (played by Nigel Hawthorne) is seen campaigning for re-election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1840-united-states-presidential-election] These scenes have been criticized for their historical inaccuracy.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The **1864 National Union National Convention** was the United States presidential nominating convention of the National Union Party, which met in Baltimore, Maryland on June 7 and 8, 1864.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] National Union was the name adopted by the main faction of the Republican Party in a coalition with many, if not most, War Democrats and Unconditional Unionists after some Republicans and War Democrats nominated John C.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont over Lincoln a few weeks earlier.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Union renominated Abraham Lincoln for president and Andrew Johnson was nominated for vice president.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] During the convention, the party adopted a platform calling for a victorious end in the ongoing Civil War, the eradication of slavery by constitutional amendment and the enforcement of the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party name was created in May 1864, during the Civil War, ahead of the 1864 presidential election, in which President Abraham Lincoln, then a Republican, was running for reelection.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] Frémont, who had been the Republicans' first presidential nominee during the 1856 election.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] It was hoped that this act would cause someone other than Lincoln to gain the Republican nomination.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] Republicans loyal to Lincoln created a new name for their party at the convention in Baltimore, Maryland, during the first week in June 1864, in order to accommodate the War Democrats who supported the war and wished to separate themselves from the Copperheads.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention dropped then-Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, a Radical Republican from the ticket, and chose War Democrat Andrew Johnson as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The National Unionists hoped that the new party and the Lincoln–Johnson ticket would stress the national character of the war.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The party supported a Platform of 11 resolutions.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] Dennis Francis Murphy, member of the Official Corps of Reporters for the U.S.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] On the first ballot, Missouri delegates cast their 22 votes for General Ulysses S.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The Missourians quickly changed their votes to make Lincoln's renomination unanimous.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] Though Hamlin was willing to serve another term as vice president, he privately made it known that he was willing to step aside if a candidate who would be a greater electoral asset to Lincoln could be found.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] The convention therefore nominated Andrew Johnson, the military governor of Tennessee.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] Lincoln had refused to weigh in on his preferred running mate, and the convention chose to nominate Johnson, a Southern War Democrat, in order to boost the party's appeal to Unionists of both parties.
[src:1864-national-union-national-convention/1864-national-union-national-convention] In keeping with the tradition of the time, Lincoln did not attend the convention.
